 title of “Evoker” by the Great God of Magic Solusek Ro himself. Likewise, his brother General Zirrix had been officially named a “Champion” by their Imperial Majesties upon gaining his 51st season as a Warrior. Tzlar was brought out of his contemplation’s by the arrival of a messenger. It was one of the agents from his guild, the Violent Harvest. Unlike his brother Zirrix, Tzlar rarely visited the guildhall. As an Arcanist he was busy traveling to far off areas of Norrath, and sometimes beyond, for his Art. Still, he did keep informed of the happenings of the Harvest. He listened to his agent’s report, then dismissed him.<br>
<br>
Tzlar considered the situation and the circumstances. First, and above all was his authority in this matter. Thankfully for his schedule, it was non-existent. This was a matter for the Triad and none other. Granted, as a member of the Harvest he had a voice in such matters, but the ultimate and final responsibility for this matter rested exclusively with the Triad, or those they assigned it to. If it were a matter of Imperial policy or social considerations, then he would indeed have a compelling input. Personally, he understood the young Thief’s attitude about Neriak. House T’Rhennic was one of the oldest of the noble Houses, and it well remembered the past. He did not know where it began, or even why, but females had indeed always held a position of power over the males in society. In fact, for millennia after the founding of the Empire, there were only Matrons leading the various Houses. The Imperial Council was composed exclusively of females, and the position of the King was downplayed in all the histories. No one seemed to know why that had changed, or when it had started. Probably because one Great House was suddenly without a Matron, and there was not a suitable female replacement. Perhaps there had been a coup in one of the more powerful of the noble families, and none of the other House’s dared strike them down. Whatever the reason, now it was not uncommon for males to have an equal, and on some matters an even  greater say, on matters of House and Empire. <br>
<br>
There were those from the “Traditional” Lines who did not accept such changes. They were in a minority, but were still a powerful force within the nobility. As Teir’dal history has shown, with but the cut of a well placed dagger, or drop of subtle poison, or well timed spell, the minority opinion of today can become the Imperial Dictate of tomorrow. Traditionalists saw equality as an example of the corruption brought about by the interaction and exposure to the lesser races. Such Lines advocated the return to isolation and consolidation of the Empire. They even called for the destruction of the foreign quarters, and extermination of all who inhabited those areas. On occasion Tzlar’s own brother Zirrix had lent his support to their cause, at least in so far as the extermination part was concerned. But, Zirrix was Second-Born and a Warrior, and it was for the Leader of the House to make “Official” policy for their Line. Tzlar knew that such gender hierarchy arguments were a dangerous thing indeed. Unless one had the resources and backing of a Great House behind them, publicly extolling such philosophies usually resulted in a sudden and silent death. In this matter Tzlar would stand by and observe the situation. He would see who was involved and, in the end, ally with the side most likely to emerge victorious. In that way, the best interests of House T’Rhennic would truly be served. Nodding in silent agreement with himself, Tzlar returned to his duties as Imperial Chancellor and the matters of the Empire.          <br>
